sql:
SELECT education_name
FROM educations
WHERE education_id > 0;

external_knowledge:
- "Blossoms of married individuals" refers to married people;
- "Stand tall in their respective fields of work" implies they are employed;
- "First to reach this level of education within their work class" refers to being the top-ranked individual in each work class based on having a bachelor's degree.

- "navigating the stormy seas of life as lone sailors" refers to individuals who have a relationship status ID of 0, which typically indicates they are not in a relationship or are living alone;
- "prestigious occupation" refers to individuals who have an occupation ID of 1, which may represent a highly respected or important job;
- "modest income" refers to individuals who have an income bracket ID of 1, which typically indicates a lower or middle-income range.

- "wise" refers to individuals with an education_id of 1, indicating a certain level of education;
- "specific lineage" refers to individuals with a race_id of 0, indicating a specific racial group;
- "moderately sized families" refers to family sizes between 2 and 5 members;
- "threshold of 30 years" means the average age of the selected individuals in a city must be greater than 30.

- 'work class' refers to the category of employment or occupation;
- 'capital gains' are the profits from the sale of property or investments;
- 'education_num' is the number of years of education an individual has completed.

- 'Bachelors' refers to a bachelor's degree in education;
- 'Sales' refers to a job in the sales industry;
- 'Husband' refers to a male individual in a marital relationship.

- "Work class" refers to the type of employment or job category of the individual;
- "Education level" indicates the highest level of education completed by the individual;
- "Native country" is the country of origin of the individual;
- "Employment status" describes whether the individual is employed, unemployed, etc.;
- "Location" is the city and state where the individual resides.

- 'Top 3' refers to the top three individuals based on hours worked per week within their education level or work class;
- 'Middle 3' includes the next three individuals based on hours worked per week within their education level or work class;
- 'Bottom' includes all other individuals outside the top and middle groups.

- 'Married-civ-spouse' refers to being married in a civilian marriage;
- 'Husband' refers to the male partner in a marriage;
- 'Employment status = 1' indicates that the individual is currently employed;
- 'Access logs' and 'location entries' are used to measure activity within the system.

- "shining stars" refers to individuals with an income bracket above the average income bracket;
- "well-educated" refers to individuals with more than 12 years of education;
- "private sector workforce" refers to individuals whose work class name starts with "Private".

- `education_id = 1` refers to a specific level of education, such as high school or college;
- `marital_status_id = 1` refers to a specific marital status, such as single or married;
- `individual_id > 0` ensures that only valid records with a positive identifier are considered.

- Employment status = 1 indicates that the individual is employed;
- Average capital gain > 10,000 signifies a higher-than-average financial gain from investments or property sales;
- Cities with a population > 100,000 are considered urban areas with significant populations.

sql:
SELECT SUM(capital_gain) AS total_capital_gain
FROM individuals
WHERE city = 'New York';

external_knowledge:
- "Most industrious individuals" refers to those who work the highest number of hours per week in their respective work classes;
- "Significant workforce" and "considerable presence" refer to work classes and marital statuses that have more than 100 and 50 individuals, respectively;
- "Harmonious order" implies the results are ordered by income bracket name and work class name, reflecting a structured and organized presentation.

- "Never-married" refers to individuals who have not been married at any point in their lives;
- "Never-worked" refers to individuals who have never been employed;
- "Doctorate" refers to the highest level of education, typically a PhD or equivalent.
